WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.890 --> 00:00:07.210
Prof: Let's start with a
brief recall of Gauss's Law.

00:00:07.210 --> 00:00:11.256
It is so important I wanted to
make sure you guys understand

00:00:11.256 --> 00:00:14.480
not only how it is used but how
it's derived.

00:00:14.480 --> 00:00:18.165
I derived it for you last time,
but I thought the presentation

00:00:18.165 --> 00:00:22.214
could be improved a little bit,
so I'm going to do it one more

00:00:22.214 --> 00:00:27.517
time,
just this time only hitting the

00:00:27.517 --> 00:00:29.390
highlights.
 

00:00:29.390 --> 00:00:33.450
The content of Gauss's Law is
very easy to visualize,

00:00:33.450 --> 00:00:35.938
so I'm going to draw you a
picture that'll tell you the

00:00:35.938 --> 00:00:37.776
whole story,
then there are all the

00:00:37.776 --> 00:00:38.350
equations.
 

00:00:38.350 --> 00:00:40.420
The picture is the following.
 

00:00:40.420 --> 00:00:45.904
You take one charge q
and you draw the lines of force

00:00:45.904 --> 00:00:48.600
coming from the one charge.
 

00:00:48.600 --> 00:00:50.330
It's a point charge.
 

00:00:50.330 --> 00:01:01.426
Therefore, you have no freedom
but to draw lines that look like

00:01:01.426 --> 00:01:02.679
this.
 

00:01:02.679 --> 00:01:07.310
Now, how many lines you draw is
a matter of convention.

00:01:07.310 --> 00:01:10.427
You can draw eight or twelve,
whatever it is,

00:01:10.427 --> 00:01:14.680
but you've got to agree that
the number per coulomb should be

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:15.390
fixed.
 

00:01:15.390 --> 00:01:17.040
So we'll fix some number.
 

00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:21.036
So I'm going to pick for
whatever charge is here these

00:01:21.036 --> 00:01:21.640
lines.
 

00:01:21.640 --> 00:01:26.104
You cannot have a distribution
of lines in which it's suddenly

00:01:26.104 --> 00:01:29.688
more dense in just this
direction, for example.

00:01:29.688 --> 00:01:33.810
That's not allowed,
because if I take this point

00:01:33.810 --> 00:01:37.274
charge and I rotate it,
it looks the same,

00:01:37.274 --> 00:01:40.565
but if I took the line
distribution with more dense

00:01:40.565 --> 00:01:43.330
here than other places if I
rotate it,

00:01:43.330 --> 00:01:46.040
it looks different.
 

00:01:46.040 --> 00:01:50.209
So if the cause of the field
lines looks the same after

00:01:50.209 --> 00:01:53.760
rotation, the effect,
which is the field lines,

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:55.459
should not change.
 

00:01:55.459 --> 00:01:58.394
You can only have a
distribution of lines with

00:01:58.394 --> 00:02:02.177
respect to symmetry of the
source of the cause of the field

00:02:02.177 --> 00:02:02.829
lines.
 

00:02:02.829 --> 00:02:04.319
You understand that?
 

00:02:04.319 --> 00:02:07.730
It cannot be biased one way or
the other, whereas this

00:02:07.730 --> 00:02:09.982
distribution,
if you turn it around,

00:02:09.982 --> 00:02:11.718
looks exactly the same.
 

00:02:11.718 --> 00:02:17.375
So we draw those lines,
and the content of Gauss's Law

00:02:17.375 --> 00:02:20.150
is really the following.
 

00:02:20.150 --> 00:02:27.527
We are going to count the lines
crossing a sphere,

00:02:27.527 --> 00:02:36.260
S, and we're going to count the
lines crossing some generic

00:02:36.260 --> 00:02:38.520
surface S'.
 

00:02:38.520 --> 00:02:45.113
You can see at a glance without
doing any calculations that the

00:02:45.113 --> 00:02:47.240
following is true.
 

00:02:47.240 --> 00:02:59.400
Lines crossing S = lines
crossing S', right?

00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:00.408
That's clear to everybody?
 

00:03:00.408 --> 00:03:02.590
You don't need to do any
equation for that.

00:03:02.590 --> 00:03:05.139
That's because the lines have
nowhere to go but out,

00:03:05.139 --> 00:03:07.038
and you can count them on this
circle,

00:03:07.038 --> 00:03:09.990
that circle as long as you
enclose the whole thing,

00:03:09.990 --> 00:03:12.098
the solid surface.
 

00:03:12.098 --> 00:03:14.830
Enclosing this charge you're
going to get the same lines.

00:03:14.830 --> 00:03:18.603
That's the heart of Gauss's
Law, but that's not the final

00:03:18.603 --> 00:03:22.038
form, but that's the part that
starts everything.

00:03:22.038 --> 00:03:24.323
Now I'm going to calculate the
left hand side,

00:03:24.323 --> 00:03:26.810
and I'm going to calculate the
right hand side.

00:03:26.810 --> 00:03:28.449
I'm going to equate them.
 

00:03:28.449 --> 00:03:32.318
From that I will get almost
everything I want.

00:03:32.318 --> 00:03:35.628
Now, how many lines are coming
out of S?

00:03:35.628 --> 00:03:39.340
We know--first the notion of
line density.

00:03:39.340 --> 00:03:42.410
I've got to remind you what a
line density is.

00:03:42.410 --> 00:03:47.961
Line density is the lines per
area, but it's not enough to say

00:03:47.961 --> 00:03:48.598
area.
 

00:03:48.598 --> 00:03:52.258
I'm going to put a
perpendicular symbol there.

00:03:52.258 --> 00:03:56.836
That means the lines are going,
say, from left to right like

00:03:56.836 --> 00:03:57.378
this.
 

00:03:57.378 --> 00:04:03.158
You want to put an area that
intercepts it perpendicularly,

00:04:03.158 --> 00:04:05.710
or if you like,
the area vector which is always

00:04:05.710 --> 00:04:08.650
normal to the area should be
parallel to the lines.

00:04:08.650 --> 00:04:11.909
So it's the number of lines
crossing unit area perpendicular

00:04:11.909 --> 00:04:12.740
to the lines.
 

00:04:12.740 --> 00:04:15.229
That's called the line density.
 

00:04:15.229 --> 00:04:17.932
If you tilted this area;
the same area,

00:04:17.932 --> 00:04:21.759
but at a bad angle,
it'll intersect fewer lines.

00:04:21.759 --> 00:04:23.449
That you know.
 

00:04:23.449 --> 00:04:25.850
Okay, so this is the meaning of
line density.

00:04:25.850 --> 00:04:29.189
What's the line density going
to look like in this problem?

00:04:29.189 --> 00:04:33.786
Line density is going to be
proportional to the charge you

00:04:33.786 --> 00:04:38.300
have because we agreed we'll put
some number of lines per

00:04:38.300 --> 00:04:42.074
coulomb,
and it's inversely proportional

00:04:42.074 --> 00:04:47.350
to the radius because the area
of a sphere of radius r

00:04:47.350 --> 00:04:49.459
is 4Πr^(2).
 

00:04:49.459 --> 00:04:52.507
So if you cut it with a bigger
sphere of bigger radius the

00:04:52.507 --> 00:04:55.449
density, lines per area,
will go like 1/r^(2).

00:04:55.449 --> 00:04:57.209
So it's proportional to
q.

00:04:57.209 --> 00:05:00.160
It's proportional to
1/r^(2),

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:00.750
okay?
 

00:05:00.750 --> 00:05:05.790
So let me write not equal to
but proportional to.

00:05:05.790 --> 00:05:08.884
You have to stop me if you
don't follow anything I'm

00:05:08.884 --> 00:05:09.430
saying.
 

00:05:09.430 --> 00:05:12.910
There's no reason why you
shouldn't follow this argument.

00:05:12.910 --> 00:05:20.519
Then I say how about the
electric field?

00:05:20.519 --> 00:05:21.629
The strength of the electric
field,

00:05:21.629 --> 00:05:25.810
not the direction,
the electric field E at

00:05:25.810 --> 00:05:30.254
radius r is also
proportional to q and

00:05:30.254 --> 00:05:33.740
also proportional to
1/r^(2).

00:05:33.740 --> 00:05:36.781
Because from Coulomb's Law the
field is the force on a unit

00:05:36.781 --> 00:05:38.617
test charge, it is
q_1q

00:05:38.617 --> 00:05:39.720
_2.
 

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:42.190
q_2 is 1
because the test charge is 1 and

00:05:42.190 --> 00:05:43.622
there's
q/4Πε

00:05:43.622 --> 00:05:44.750
_0r^(2).
 

00:05:44.750 --> 00:05:45.940
Forget the 4Π.
 

00:05:45.940 --> 00:05:49.629
It's proportional to
q/r^(2).

00:05:49.629 --> 00:05:53.187
From this we may conclude that
the line density is proportional

00:05:53.187 --> 00:05:56.516
to the electric field because
they are both proportional to

00:05:56.516 --> 00:05:58.009
q/r^(2).
 

00:05:58.009 --> 00:06:05.406
Therefore, we can say line
density is equal to some

00:06:05.406 --> 00:06:12.949
constant c times the electric
field in magnitude;

00:06:12.949 --> 00:06:17.350
direction of the lines is along
E, but the magnitude.

00:06:17.350 --> 00:06:18.420
Do you understand that?
 

00:06:18.420 --> 00:06:20.589
This guy is proportional to
this.

00:06:20.589 --> 00:06:22.307
This may have some
proportionality constant,

00:06:22.307 --> 00:06:24.463
this may have another one,
but nothing changes the fact

00:06:24.463 --> 00:06:26.540
that this expression's
proportional to that one.

00:06:26.540 --> 00:06:28.449
The constant will depend on
details.

00:06:28.449 --> 00:06:31.879
Let me just call it some number
c.

00:06:31.879 --> 00:06:32.949
c is up to you.
 

00:06:32.949 --> 00:06:35.834
It really depends on how many
lines you want to draw per

00:06:35.834 --> 00:06:36.360
coulomb.
 

00:06:36.360 --> 00:06:37.976
I made a particular choice last
time,

00:06:37.976 --> 00:06:40.129
1/ε_0
lines per coulomb,

00:06:40.129 --> 00:06:42.509
but you don't have to make that
to prove the law.

00:06:42.509 --> 00:06:46.262
So this time I'm just assuming
the lines is proportional to

00:06:46.262 --> 00:06:49.949
charge, but you pick your own
proportionality constant.

00:06:49.949 --> 00:06:53.682
So I've got this line density
that's proportional to electric

00:06:53.682 --> 00:06:54.180
field.
 

00:06:54.180 --> 00:06:58.708
Now I'm going to go back and
I'm going to calculate the left

00:06:58.708 --> 00:06:59.629
hand side.
 

00:06:59.629 --> 00:07:03.639
Now, let's give this equation a
number, equation number 1.

00:07:03.639 --> 00:07:11.550
I'm going to calculate the left
hand side of 1.

00:07:11.550 --> 00:07:17.476
Left hand side of 1 is the
number of lines crossing this

00:07:17.476 --> 00:07:18.769
sphere, S.
 

00:07:18.769 --> 00:07:25.000
So that's going to be equal
to--let me call it

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:31.509
Φ_S is equal to
number crossing S,

00:07:31.509 --> 00:07:35.250
crossing this sphere S.
 

00:07:35.250 --> 00:07:38.560
Φ is the standard symbol
for flux.

00:07:38.560 --> 00:07:41.290
So what is it?
 

00:07:41.290 --> 00:08:04.810
Well, Φ_S = line
density times area of sphere,

00:08:04.810 --> 00:08:07.949
because on a sphere the lines
are uniform in density so the

00:08:07.949 --> 00:08:11.305
total number crossing the sphere
is the line density times area

00:08:11.305 --> 00:08:12.278
of the sphere.
 

00:08:12.278 --> 00:08:17.637
But the line density is a
constant times the electric

00:08:17.637 --> 00:08:24.024
field at radius r (if you
like) times area of the sphere

00:08:24.024 --> 00:08:27.220
which is 4Πr^(2).
 

00:08:27.220 --> 00:08:32.086
That's the lines crossing the
inner surface which is this

00:08:32.086 --> 00:08:34.519
sphere of radius r.
 

00:08:34.519 --> 00:08:46.350
Now, Φ_S' is
lines crossing S'.

00:08:46.350 --> 00:08:50.128
Now you've got to be a little
careful when you find the lines

00:08:50.128 --> 00:08:51.009
crossing S'.
 

00:08:51.009 --> 00:08:54.158
You understand why that's more
difficult?

00:08:54.158 --> 00:08:59.767
What are the two complications
in finding the lines crossing S'

00:08:59.767 --> 00:09:04.200
compared to this one which I did
in one second?

00:09:04.200 --> 00:09:04.899
Any idea?
 

00:09:04.899 --> 00:09:05.950
Yes?
 

00:09:05.950 --> 00:09:07.808
Student:  The normals
are all parallel to the field

00:09:07.808 --> 00:09:08.070
lines?
 

00:09:08.070 --> 00:09:09.139
Prof: Which is not
parallel?

00:09:09.139 --> 00:09:10.591
Student:  The normal to
the surface isn't parallel to

00:09:10.591 --> 00:09:10.960
the ________.
 

00:09:10.960 --> 00:09:13.600
Prof: Okay,
the surface is not--surface

00:09:13.600 --> 00:09:17.178
vector at each point is not
parallel to the electric field.

00:09:17.178 --> 00:09:19.480
For example,
if you've got a crazy surface

00:09:19.480 --> 00:09:22.066
like this--
I'll try to replicate that

00:09:22.066 --> 00:09:24.417
surface,
but I don't remember what I

00:09:24.417 --> 00:09:26.538
drew, some weird object like
this.

00:09:26.538 --> 00:09:31.745
Then the electric field point
this way, but the normal to the

00:09:31.745 --> 00:09:34.350
surface will point that way.
 

00:09:34.350 --> 00:09:36.158
See, E points that way.
 

00:09:36.158 --> 00:09:38.342
Tiny area there,
which I'm calling vector

00:09:38.342 --> 00:09:40.798
dA, points in a different
direction.

00:09:40.798 --> 00:09:43.798
So each region has a different
direction.

00:09:43.798 --> 00:09:48.272
Secondly, the strength of the
field itself is varying on the

00:09:48.272 --> 00:09:49.029
surface.
 

00:09:49.029 --> 00:09:51.470
Unlike on a sphere where
everything is at the same

00:09:51.470 --> 00:09:54.158
distance r some are
further, some are closer.

00:09:54.158 --> 00:09:57.788
But it is still true that if
you want the number of lines

00:09:57.788 --> 00:10:00.970
cross a patch,
if you pick a little area here,

00:10:00.970 --> 00:10:04.796
if you want to know how many
lines cross that you take the

00:10:04.796 --> 00:10:08.677
normal to the area,
call it a vector dA,

00:10:08.677 --> 00:10:11.620
and you multiply by line
density.

00:10:11.620 --> 00:10:17.038
Therefore, this is equal to the
integral of the electric field

00:10:17.038 --> 00:10:22.014
at some point r dot
product with a tiny area which

00:10:22.014 --> 00:10:23.168
is there.
 

00:10:23.168 --> 00:10:28.528
At each region you've got to
draw a different dA.

00:10:28.528 --> 00:10:32.029
So you take the surface,
you chop it up into tiny little

00:10:32.029 --> 00:10:32.538
tiles.
 

00:10:32.538 --> 00:10:35.389
Each tile is small enough to be
considered a plane.

00:10:35.389 --> 00:10:38.543
Then the area vector is
perpendicular to the plane,

00:10:38.543 --> 00:10:41.951
outward from the surface,
and of magnitude equal to the

00:10:41.951 --> 00:10:43.970
numerical area of the plane.
 

00:10:43.970 --> 00:10:47.172
So the lines crossing every
tiny little square on the big

00:10:47.172 --> 00:10:50.490
surface is the number of lines
per unit area times the area

00:10:50.490 --> 00:10:53.350
times the cosine of the angle
which you need,

00:10:53.350 --> 00:10:58.000
because the area vector may not
be parallel to the flow.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:01.710
I have explained many times why
the flow there,

00:11:01.710 --> 00:11:04.067
the flow vector and the area
vector are not parallel you've

00:11:04.067 --> 00:11:05.528
got to put in a
cosθ.

00:11:05.528 --> 00:11:10.139
That's what comes into this dot
product.

00:11:10.139 --> 00:11:12.653
And we write the symbol like
this to tell you not only is it

00:11:12.653 --> 00:11:14.676
a double integral,
meaning integral over a

00:11:14.676 --> 00:11:17.405
two-dimensional region,
but it's over a closed

00:11:17.405 --> 00:11:19.049
two-dimensional region.
 

00:11:19.049 --> 00:11:22.759
That symbol is to remind you.
 

00:11:22.759 --> 00:11:26.188
So now, Φ_S equal
to Φ_S' is what

00:11:26.188 --> 00:11:27.389
I'm going to write.
 

00:11:27.389 --> 00:11:29.418
So I'm going to write--oh,
I made one mistake.

00:11:29.418 --> 00:11:36.820
Can anybody see one thing
missing in this equation here?

00:11:36.820 --> 00:11:39.389
This equation's not correct.
 

00:11:39.389 --> 00:11:44.330
To find the lines crossing S' I
took E times dA.

00:11:44.330 --> 00:11:48.038
It's a constant c
because the line density is not

00:11:48.038 --> 00:11:51.139
simply the electric field it's
the constant.

00:11:51.139 --> 00:11:56.351
So I forgot the constant,
but I knew that I would need it

00:11:56.351 --> 00:12:00.538
because when I now equate
Φ_S to

00:12:00.538 --> 00:12:05.284
Φ_S' I get
constant times the electric

00:12:05.284 --> 00:12:10.124
field at r times
4Πr^(2) is equal to

00:12:10.124 --> 00:12:13.567
constant times the surface
integral of

00:12:13.567 --> 00:12:18.500
E⋅dA on some
surface S'.

00:12:18.500 --> 00:12:21.476
But E(r) times
4Πr^(2) is c

00:12:21.476 --> 00:12:23.306
times
q/ε_0

00:12:23.306 --> 00:12:25.500
because E is
q/4Πε

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:27.120
_0r^(2).
 

00:12:27.120 --> 00:12:28.139
You see that?
 

00:12:28.139 --> 00:12:29.090
This much you should know.
 

00:12:29.090 --> 00:12:30.730
I'm not going to write the
details.

00:12:30.730 --> 00:12:38.155
So that is equal to c
times surface integral of

00:12:38.155 --> 00:12:41.798
E⋅dA.
 

00:12:41.798 --> 00:12:45.330
Now you see the constant does
not matter,

00:12:45.330 --> 00:12:49.562
so whatever the constant is I
can make the following statement

00:12:49.562 --> 00:12:53.308
and that's going to be the
beginning of Gauss's Law.

00:12:53.308 --> 00:12:57.529
So Gauss's Law tells me that if
you took a charge and you sat

00:12:57.529 --> 00:13:01.539
under it with any surface
whatsoever--I'm not going to put

00:13:01.539 --> 00:13:03.509
a prime on this anymore.
 

00:13:03.509 --> 00:13:05.778
S is going to be the surface.
 

00:13:05.778 --> 00:13:11.682
Then the surface integral of
the electric field due to that

00:13:11.682 --> 00:13:17.688
charge over a surface is equal
to the charge that is sitting

00:13:17.688 --> 00:13:22.269
inside divided by
ε_0,

00:13:22.269 --> 00:13:25.379
and it does not depend on the
details of the surface.

00:13:25.379 --> 00:13:35.259
 
 

00:13:35.259 --> 00:13:39.808
Okay, everybody should know in
principle how to do the surface

00:13:39.808 --> 00:13:40.629
integral.
 

00:13:40.629 --> 00:13:42.995
If I give you a surface,
and at the surface at every

00:13:42.995 --> 00:13:44.759
point I give you a vector
E,

00:13:44.759 --> 00:13:47.393
which is electric field,
you should know how to

00:13:47.393 --> 00:13:48.940
numerically calculate it.
 

00:13:48.940 --> 00:13:52.072
You may not know how to do the
integral analytically,

00:13:52.072 --> 00:13:55.267
but operationally you should
know the meaning of this,

00:13:55.267 --> 00:13:55.808
okay?
 

00:13:55.808 --> 00:13:58.672
If E were actually the
velocity of some stuff running

00:13:58.672 --> 00:14:01.389
out of the volume you're
counting in each region how many

00:14:01.389 --> 00:14:04.350
guys are escaping per second and
you're adding it all up.

00:14:04.350 --> 00:14:06.820
And to find how many guys are
leaving a tiny area,

00:14:06.820 --> 00:14:09.653
you multiply the area by the
velocity of flow times the

00:14:09.653 --> 00:14:12.539
cosine of the angle between the
velocity in the area.

00:14:12.539 --> 00:14:14.610
That's it.
 

00:14:14.610 --> 00:14:18.038
Okay, now we do the next thing.
 

00:14:18.038 --> 00:14:24.572
Let's call this charge
q_1 because I'm

00:14:24.572 --> 00:14:31.590
now going to put a second guy
q_2 here.

00:14:31.590 --> 00:14:34.283
If you now think in terms of
lines of force you're going to

00:14:34.283 --> 00:14:36.418
get into a big mess because
lines of force,

00:14:36.418 --> 00:14:38.529
due to two charges is a
complicated thing,

00:14:38.529 --> 00:14:40.409
you remember drawing some
pictures.

00:14:40.409 --> 00:14:42.009
But now here's the beauty.
 

00:14:42.009 --> 00:14:45.288
Forget the lines of force
completely, not interested.

00:14:45.288 --> 00:14:48.629
I'm interested in the electric
field.

00:14:48.629 --> 00:14:52.269
Focus on the electric field for
which there's a very simple

00:14:52.269 --> 00:14:52.710
rule.
 

00:14:52.710 --> 00:14:58.245
The electric field due to two
charges 1 and 2 is the electric

00:14:58.245 --> 00:15:02.860
field due to 1 plus the electric
field due to 2.

00:15:02.860 --> 00:15:10.149
That's the great principle of
superposition.

00:15:10.149 --> 00:15:14.370
Therefore, on the left hand
side you might say if both

00:15:14.370 --> 00:15:17.636
charges are inside the surface
integral of

00:15:17.636 --> 00:15:21.937
E_1,2_
meaning when both are

00:15:21.937 --> 00:15:26.318
present is equal to surface
integral of E_1

00:15:26.318 --> 00:15:30.700
⋅dA surface
integral of E_2

00:15:30.700 --> 00:15:35.371
⋅dA,
because E_1,2

00:15:35.371 --> 00:15:38.750
is E_1
E_2.

00:15:38.750 --> 00:15:40.851
But the first guy is
q_1

00:15:40.851 --> 00:15:43.070
/ε
_0,

00:15:43.070 --> 00:15:47.833
second is q_2
/ε

00:15:47.833 --> 00:15:49.940
_0.
 

00:15:49.940 --> 00:15:54.038
Once you can do two charges you
can do any number of charges.

00:15:54.038 --> 00:15:57.950
And now we write Gauss's Law
almost in its final form.

00:15:57.950 --> 00:16:02.278
The final form is that if you
took the total electric field,

00:16:02.278 --> 00:16:05.811
I'm not going to put total,
E will stand for the

00:16:05.811 --> 00:16:09.490
total,
on a surface S that is

00:16:09.490 --> 00:16:13.538
equal to the sum of all the
charges,

00:16:13.538 --> 00:16:16.580
i from 1 to whatever
many charges you have,

00:16:16.580 --> 00:16:18.389
divided by
ε_0.

00:16:18.389 --> 00:16:22.523
The condition is these are
charges inside the volume

00:16:22.523 --> 00:16:24.548
bounded by the surface.
 

00:16:24.548 --> 00:16:27.538
You do not count the charge
here.

00:16:27.538 --> 00:16:31.740
You only count charges which
are inside not charges which are

00:16:31.740 --> 00:16:32.440
outside.
 

00:16:32.440 --> 00:16:37.794
So let's make a notation that
tells you that i is

00:16:37.794 --> 00:16:40.620
inside the volume V.
 

00:16:40.620 --> 00:16:44.470
And this surface is the
boundary of the volume V.

00:16:44.470 --> 00:16:49.336
This partial derivative symbol
is the universal convention for

00:16:49.336 --> 00:16:51.649
the boundary of any region.
 

00:16:51.649 --> 00:16:56.149
Okay, if you draw a real
circle, this is the circle.

00:16:56.149 --> 00:17:00.580
The boundary of the circle is
this.

00:17:00.580 --> 00:17:02.836
If you a have a cube,
or if you have an orange the

00:17:02.836 --> 00:17:05.509
boundary of the volume orange is
the skin of the orange.

00:17:05.509 --> 00:17:07.048
That's the definition of
boundary.

00:17:07.048 --> 00:17:09.740
You can see this is like the
skin of the solid region,

00:17:09.740 --> 00:17:14.650
and the surface integral on the
skin of the electric field is a

00:17:14.650 --> 00:17:18.768
charge inside the volume
whatever be the shape of the

00:17:18.768 --> 00:17:19.640
volume.
 

00:17:19.640 --> 00:17:21.440
And it works for all kinds of
surfaces.

00:17:21.440 --> 00:17:23.690
I mean, here's one example.
 

00:17:23.690 --> 00:17:25.509
Suppose you have a charge here.
 

00:17:25.509 --> 00:17:29.009
You take a surface that kind of
intersects itself and so on.

00:17:29.009 --> 00:17:33.650
Then what can happen is if I
put a charge here the lines may

00:17:33.650 --> 00:17:34.828
go like this.
 

00:17:34.828 --> 00:17:38.769
It doesn't matter because over
this when it switches back on

00:17:38.769 --> 00:17:41.509
itself some lines leave,
some lines enter,

00:17:41.509 --> 00:17:43.578
and some lines leave again.
 

00:17:43.578 --> 00:17:48.846
So it might as well be that
surface because double entering

00:17:48.846 --> 00:17:51.480
and leaving doesn't matter.
 

00:17:51.480 --> 00:17:55.757
So the rule is if q is
inside it contributes to the

00:17:55.757 --> 00:17:58.909
surface integral,
if q is outside it

00:17:58.909 --> 00:17:59.808
doesn't.
 

00:17:59.808 --> 00:18:03.608
The last variation is what if
q is not made up of a

00:18:03.608 --> 00:18:07.037
discrete set of charges,
which you can say one is here

00:18:07.037 --> 00:18:09.866
one is there,
but there's some continuous

00:18:09.866 --> 00:18:13.769
blob, some lump of charge where
the charge density--

00:18:13.769 --> 00:18:20.598
so then we say suppose q
is continuous.

00:18:20.598 --> 00:18:22.868
You've got to realize in real
life it's never continuous.

00:18:22.868 --> 00:18:25.618
Real charges are made up of
electrons and protons.

00:18:25.618 --> 00:18:28.654
They are discrete,
but if your eye is not looking

00:18:28.654 --> 00:18:32.640
at it in great detail the charge
can appear to be continuous.

00:18:32.640 --> 00:18:34.763
For example,
if you take a glass of water

00:18:34.763 --> 00:18:37.420
the water is really made up of
point molecules,

00:18:37.420 --> 00:18:40.134
water molecules,
but to your eye it looks like a

00:18:40.134 --> 00:18:41.288
continuous medium.
 

00:18:41.288 --> 00:18:45.492
So for certain purposes we can
replace a discrete distribution

00:18:45.492 --> 00:18:47.009
by a continuous one.
 

00:18:47.009 --> 00:18:50.550
For a continuous distribution
what you have to tell me is the

00:18:50.550 --> 00:18:51.259
following.
 

00:18:51.259 --> 00:18:53.559
This is space x,
y, and z.

00:18:53.559 --> 00:18:55.480
Here's the point.
 

00:18:55.480 --> 00:19:01.670
I take a tiny cube whose sides
are dx,

00:19:01.670 --> 00:19:07.519
dy and dz,
and ρ of x,

00:19:07.519 --> 00:19:16.380
y, and z times
dxdydz is equal to charge

00:19:16.380 --> 00:19:19.630
in that little cube.
 

00:19:19.630 --> 00:19:22.909
In other words,
like the usual density with

00:19:22.909 --> 00:19:27.361
this mass per unit volume the
ρ is the charge per unit

00:19:27.361 --> 00:19:28.220
volume.
 

00:19:28.220 --> 00:19:30.858
So you multiply by volume you
get the charge,

00:19:30.858 --> 00:19:32.598
but it need not be uniform.
 

00:19:32.598 --> 00:19:41.453
So if you have a solid region
then the charge density could be

00:19:41.453 --> 00:19:46.390
varying from point to point,
so.

00:19:46.390 --> 00:19:48.548
Oh, let's keep it here.
 

00:19:48.548 --> 00:19:54.186
In that case you will write the
surface integral of

00:19:54.186 --> 00:20:00.614
E⋅dA over a
surface that binds a volume

00:20:00.614 --> 00:20:05.799
V would be
1/ε_0 times

00:20:05.799 --> 00:20:10.309
the volume integral of ρ
of (x, y,

00:20:10.309 --> 00:20:13.578
z) dxdydz.
 

00:20:13.578 --> 00:20:24.670
This is the final form of
Gauss's Law.

00:20:24.670 --> 00:20:31.980
Now, how many people have ever
done integrals in more than one

00:20:31.980 --> 00:20:33.420
dimension?
 

00:20:33.420 --> 00:20:38.185
Great, very good,
made my day because I didn't

00:20:38.185 --> 00:20:39.670
have Plan B.
 

00:20:39.670 --> 00:20:44.093
But I did--no actually I had a
Plan Tiny B which is to give you

00:20:44.093 --> 00:20:45.519
a quick refresher.
 

00:20:45.519 --> 00:20:49.290
If there is time at the end of
the class I will remind you of

00:20:49.290 --> 00:20:51.680
how the multiple integrals are
done.

00:20:51.680 --> 00:20:54.758
But right now I'm going to show
you the efficacy of this law and

00:20:54.758 --> 00:20:57.250
that doesn't require doing
complicated integrals.

00:20:57.250 --> 00:21:01.771
All the integrals will be so
trivial you can just read them

00:21:01.771 --> 00:21:02.240
off.
 

00:21:02.240 --> 00:21:06.038
So when we have time we'll do
questions of how to do these

00:21:06.038 --> 00:21:10.368
integrals, but I'm assuming this
symbol means something to you.

00:21:10.368 --> 00:21:12.558
In words it means all the
charge inside.

00:21:12.558 --> 00:21:15.461
So, again, by taking the
volume, dividing into tiny

00:21:15.461 --> 00:21:17.425
regions,
multiplying each volume,

00:21:17.425 --> 00:21:19.393
tiny volume,
by the density to get the

00:21:19.393 --> 00:21:21.602
charge there,
and summing over all the

00:21:21.602 --> 00:21:24.089
volumes inside the big volume
V.

00:21:24.089 --> 00:21:25.068
That's a charge.
 

00:21:25.068 --> 00:21:28.670
So Gauss's Law still says the
surface integral of E is

00:21:28.670 --> 00:21:30.769
the charge inside over epsilon
0.

00:21:30.769 --> 00:21:33.990
All right, so this is the great
law.

00:21:33.990 --> 00:21:37.776
Now we're going to get some
mileage out of it to solve

00:21:37.776 --> 00:21:41.920
certain problems which normally
would be very difficult.

00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:45.479
The first problem,
I think I probably did that

00:21:45.479 --> 00:21:50.145
last time but it's worth going
over, is what is the electric

00:21:50.145 --> 00:21:53.390
field of a uniform density of
charge.

00:21:53.390 --> 00:21:59.602
Suppose there's a charge
Q and this is sphere of

00:21:59.602 --> 00:22:04.433
radius r,
and it is a ball of radius

00:22:04.433 --> 00:22:05.930
r.
 

00:22:05.930 --> 00:22:07.888
You take all these charges and
you pile them on top of each

00:22:07.888 --> 00:22:08.160
other.
 

00:22:08.160 --> 00:22:10.042
They don't like it,
but you glue them or do

00:22:10.042 --> 00:22:11.210
whatever you have to do.
 

00:22:11.210 --> 00:22:13.720
You've got a ball of charge
Q.

00:22:13.720 --> 00:22:16.160
You want the field due to that.
 

00:22:16.160 --> 00:22:18.660
It's the same problem Newton
had with gravity.

00:22:18.660 --> 00:22:20.528
The earth is a solid ball.
 

00:22:20.528 --> 00:22:24.242
It's got mass everywhere and
you would like to find the force

00:22:24.242 --> 00:22:25.108
on an apple.
 

00:22:25.108 --> 00:22:29.189
And it's not so evident that
the force of the earth on the

00:22:29.189 --> 00:22:33.769
apple is as if the entire mass
of the earth but at the center.

00:22:33.769 --> 00:22:35.210
You have to prove that.
 

00:22:35.210 --> 00:22:38.180
You have to prove that by
dividing the earth into little

00:22:38.180 --> 00:22:40.881
pieces and finding the
gravitational force of every

00:22:40.881 --> 00:22:44.230
little piece on the apple and
adding all those vectors up.

00:22:44.230 --> 00:22:45.940
And when you do all the hard
work you will find,

00:22:45.940 --> 00:22:48.798
in fact, that it's true,
but it took Newton several

00:22:48.798 --> 00:22:52.285
years to prove that even though
he was pretty certain that was

00:22:52.285 --> 00:22:52.798
true.
 

00:22:52.798 --> 00:22:55.555
That's very important because
when you do the force law for

00:22:55.555 --> 00:22:57.740
apple versus the earth the
distance you use for

00:22:57.740 --> 00:23:00.068
m_1m
_2/r^(2) is

00:23:00.068 --> 00:23:02.967
a center-to-center distance as
if the entire earth were at the

00:23:02.967 --> 00:23:03.680
center.
 

00:23:03.680 --> 00:23:06.490
A similar law is true for
electric forces.

00:23:06.490 --> 00:23:08.806
In other words,
if you've got a spherical

00:23:08.806 --> 00:23:12.511
distribution of charge the field
due to that outside that ball is

00:23:12.511 --> 00:23:15.058
as if all the charge were at the
center.

00:23:15.058 --> 00:23:18.497
That's what we want to prove,
but we want to prove that

00:23:18.497 --> 00:23:22.188
without doing any difficult
integrals, and the trick is the

00:23:22.188 --> 00:23:23.078
following.
 

00:23:23.078 --> 00:23:26.972
You are going to use Gauss's
Law, and you can use Gauss's Law

00:23:26.972 --> 00:23:28.660
on any surface you like.
 

00:23:28.660 --> 00:23:32.029
For example,
you can take that surface and

00:23:32.029 --> 00:23:36.715
you can say surface integral of
E on the surface is

00:23:36.715 --> 00:23:40.695
Q/ε_0,
but that's not very helpful

00:23:40.695 --> 00:23:44.066
because what you're trying to
find out is not the electric

00:23:44.066 --> 00:23:46.490
field integrated over a whole
region,

00:23:46.490 --> 00:23:48.500
but the electric field at each
point.

00:23:48.500 --> 00:23:52.690
You want to know what's going
on right there.

00:23:52.690 --> 00:23:55.823
So even though it's a true
statement that whatever E

00:23:55.823 --> 00:23:57.875
is doing its integral on any
surface is

00:23:57.875 --> 00:24:00.684
Q/ε_0 that
doesn't tell you what is

00:24:00.684 --> 00:24:04.451
E at every point,
and we're going to find that by

00:24:04.451 --> 00:24:05.869
the following trick.
 

00:24:05.869 --> 00:24:08.980
The trick is to first decide.
 

00:24:08.980 --> 00:24:12.041
This surface S,
by the way, it's called a

00:24:12.041 --> 00:24:13.279
Gaussian surface.
 

00:24:13.279 --> 00:24:16.420
It's not a real surface.
 

00:24:16.420 --> 00:24:18.670
In real life there are no
Gaussian surfaces.

00:24:18.670 --> 00:24:21.453
You draw them for a
calculation, and you can move it

00:24:21.453 --> 00:24:24.674
around in your mind anyway you
like, for each surface you'll

00:24:24.674 --> 00:24:26.150
get a different answer.
 

00:24:26.150 --> 00:24:34.173
We'll pick a Gaussian surface
equal to a sphere of radius

00:24:34.173 --> 00:24:35.750
r.
 

00:24:35.750 --> 00:24:49.420
So I'm going to pick a Gaussian
surface of radius r.

00:24:49.420 --> 00:24:52.395
I'm going to argue two things
and you have to follow the

00:24:52.395 --> 00:24:55.210
reasoning because all the work
is in the argument.

00:24:55.210 --> 00:24:58.526
You don't do any integrals,
but you do some serious

00:24:58.526 --> 00:24:59.190
arguing.
 

00:24:59.190 --> 00:25:03.140
The arguing says it's a ball,
positive charge.

00:25:03.140 --> 00:25:04.630
It's going to repel a test
charge.

00:25:04.630 --> 00:25:06.950
Which way is the repulsion
going to be at this point?

00:25:06.950 --> 00:25:09.700
It has to be radially away from
the center.

00:25:09.700 --> 00:25:11.328
That's your argument.
 

00:25:11.328 --> 00:25:15.578
At each point the repulsion has
to be away from the center.

00:25:15.578 --> 00:25:18.144
In other words the electric
field has to have this

00:25:18.144 --> 00:25:18.930
distribution.
 

00:25:18.930 --> 00:25:21.694
We're not saying how it varies
with distance,

00:25:21.694 --> 00:25:23.328
but it has to be radial.
 

00:25:23.328 --> 00:25:27.057
Again, the argument is the
radially outgoing thing like a

00:25:27.057 --> 00:25:27.788
hedgehog.
 

00:25:27.788 --> 00:25:31.001
It's the only distribution of
lines which will look the same

00:25:31.001 --> 00:25:34.160
if you rotate them because then
one line will go to another

00:25:34.160 --> 00:25:34.650
line.
 

00:25:34.650 --> 00:25:37.568
The hedgehog will look exactly
the same.

00:25:37.568 --> 00:25:40.757
And that is a necessary
requirement because if you took

00:25:40.757 --> 00:25:44.063
this ball of charge you all
understand that if you rotate

00:25:44.063 --> 00:25:47.663
the ball the field lines have to
rotate due to any calculation

00:25:47.663 --> 00:25:50.269
you did,
but if you rotate the ball it

00:25:50.269 --> 00:25:51.220
looks the same.
 

00:25:51.220 --> 00:25:52.660
So the field lines have to look
the same.

00:25:52.660 --> 00:25:55.969
So the distribution you draw
must be invariant under that

00:25:55.969 --> 00:25:56.618
rotation.
 

00:25:56.618 --> 00:25:59.586
This is a very powerful
principle of symmetry and

00:25:59.586 --> 00:26:00.390
invariance.
 

00:26:00.390 --> 00:26:03.960
The principle says if something
is the cause of something,

00:26:03.960 --> 00:26:07.390
and if I do something to the
cause that leaves it alone,

00:26:07.390 --> 00:26:09.755
namely it looks the same,
the effect has to look the

00:26:09.755 --> 00:26:10.079
same.
 

00:26:10.079 --> 00:26:12.009
It's a very reasonable argument.
 

00:26:12.009 --> 00:26:15.217
And the cause here is a ball of
charge which is completely

00:26:15.217 --> 00:26:16.680
isotropic and spherical.
 

00:26:16.680 --> 00:26:18.163
You turn it,
it looks the same,

00:26:18.163 --> 00:26:20.288
so the field distribution looks
the same.

00:26:20.288 --> 00:26:23.624
That's all you need to proceed
because that distribution then

00:26:23.624 --> 00:26:26.568
is going to have radial lines of
unknown strength,

00:26:26.568 --> 00:26:29.059
but the strength can vary only
with r,

00:26:29.059 --> 00:26:30.368
but not at a given r.
 

00:26:30.368 --> 00:26:32.612
At a given r the
direction varies,

00:26:32.612 --> 00:26:35.135
but the strength is some E
of r,

00:26:35.135 --> 00:26:37.940
and we're asking what is
E of r?

00:26:37.940 --> 00:26:41.711
So we know that E looks
like r,

00:26:41.711 --> 00:26:46.685
which is the vector of length
in the radial direction times

00:26:46.685 --> 00:26:48.828
E of r.
 

00:26:48.828 --> 00:26:52.438
And sometimes I also write this
as e_r times

00:26:52.438 --> 00:26:55.565
E of r,
and we just want to know what E

00:26:55.565 --> 00:26:57.369
is a function of r.
 

00:26:57.369 --> 00:27:00.980
But now we can use Gauss's Law.
 

00:27:00.980 --> 00:27:04.778
So the left hand side is a
surface integral of this radial

00:27:04.778 --> 00:27:07.578
E on a sphere of radius
r.

00:27:07.578 --> 00:27:12.230
That's going to be E
times 4Πr^(2),

00:27:12.230 --> 00:27:16.608
because E is a constant
on the surface.

00:27:16.608 --> 00:27:18.881
The integral of a constant on
the surface is the constant

00:27:18.881 --> 00:27:20.180
times the area of the surface.
 

00:27:20.180 --> 00:27:23.794
It's like saying if you want to
integrate a function which is

00:27:23.794 --> 00:27:27.468
constant from here to here it's
the constant height multiplied

00:27:27.468 --> 00:27:30.480
by the interval over which
you're integrating.

00:27:30.480 --> 00:27:31.750
There's no integral to do.
 

00:27:31.750 --> 00:27:33.119
It's very trivial.
 

00:27:33.119 --> 00:27:34.390
It's a rectangle.
 

00:27:34.390 --> 00:27:37.396
Similarly a constant function
integrated on a sphere is the

00:27:37.396 --> 00:27:39.678
area times this,
but E is the function

00:27:39.678 --> 00:27:41.130
of, of course,
r.

00:27:41.130 --> 00:27:43.019
That's going to be charge
enclosed.

00:27:43.019 --> 00:27:45.432
The charge enclosed is Q
and you've got to put the

00:27:45.432 --> 00:27:48.229
ε_0,
and then you find

00:27:48.229 --> 00:27:52.980
E(r) is
Q/4Πε

00:27:52.980 --> 00:27:55.509
_0r^(2).
 

00:27:55.509 --> 00:28:02.199
And if you want to put all the
vectors back you can write here

00:28:02.199 --> 00:28:05.380
times e_r.
 

00:28:05.380 --> 00:28:10.837
So by this trick one can show
that the field of a sphere is as

00:28:10.837 --> 00:28:14.150
if the charges were at the
center,

00:28:14.150 --> 00:28:21.650
provided you are talking about
a point outside the sphere.

00:28:21.650 --> 00:28:25.020
As long as this field is
outside the real ball no matter

00:28:25.020 --> 00:28:27.962
what its radius is,
the charge enclosed is always

00:28:27.962 --> 00:28:28.759
Q.
 

00:28:28.759 --> 00:28:30.868
The right hand side doesn't
vary with Q.

00:28:30.868 --> 00:28:33.829
The left hand side looks like r
squared times electric field so

00:28:33.829 --> 00:28:35.548
E goes like
1/r^(2).

00:28:35.548 --> 00:28:39.180
But now I'm going to do some
variations on this.

00:28:39.180 --> 00:28:46.712
The first variation is what if
I want the electric field at

00:28:46.712 --> 00:28:50.220
some point here,
in here?

