00:31:54.349 --> 00:31:55.740
Yeah, that's right.
 

00:31:55.740 --> 00:31:57.690
Student:  Gotcha.
 

00:31:57.690 --> 00:32:00.474
Prof: Okay,
eternally vigilant,

00:32:00.474 --> 00:32:01.529
that's good.
 

00:32:01.529 --> 00:32:02.588
Yes?
 

00:32:02.588 --> 00:32:05.420
Student:  What if little
r equals big R?

00:32:05.420 --> 00:32:06.308
Prof: Let's ask.
 

00:32:06.308 --> 00:32:09.598
What if little r grows
up and become big R,

00:32:09.598 --> 00:32:10.069
right?
 

00:32:10.069 --> 00:32:11.289
We'll find out.
 

00:32:11.289 --> 00:32:13.769
What do you expect?
 

00:32:13.769 --> 00:32:16.501
You've got to get the same
answer at the field at a certain

00:32:16.501 --> 00:32:18.198
point no matter how we
approached it,

00:32:18.198 --> 00:32:18.670
right?
 

00:32:18.670 --> 00:32:20.890
You'll find that's true in this
formula,

00:32:20.890 --> 00:32:25.373
because if you put little
r equals big R and

00:32:25.373 --> 00:32:29.384
big R over big
R^(3) you'll get 1 over

00:32:29.384 --> 00:32:33.632
big R^(2) and this will
also give you 1 over big

00:32:33.632 --> 00:32:38.036
R^(2). These formulas
will match on the surface of

00:32:38.036 --> 00:32:39.609
this sphere.
 

00:32:39.609 --> 00:32:42.038
Yes?
 

00:32:42.038 --> 00:32:46.071
Student:  So can you say
again why we can assume that we

00:32:46.071 --> 00:32:49.779
