00:33:05.220 --> 00:33:07.160
E⋅dA, right?
 

00:33:07.160 --> 00:33:11.348
If I did that it'll be fine
with you, correct?

00:33:11.348 --> 00:33:17.490
This is what you're saying I
should do, right?

00:33:17.490 --> 00:33:19.663
You asked me why I didn't do
this integral,

00:33:19.663 --> 00:33:21.423
why I just wrote
4Πr^(2),

00:33:21.423 --> 00:33:22.769
is that your question?
 

00:33:22.769 --> 00:33:24.430
Right.
 

00:33:24.430 --> 00:33:29.096
The assumed form for E
is the function that depends on

00:33:29.096 --> 00:33:33.220
r times unit vector in
the radial direction.

00:33:33.220 --> 00:33:38.154
And since I surrounded it with
this sphere the tiny area vector

00:33:38.154 --> 00:33:42.532
is also e_r
times the value of the tiny

00:33:42.532 --> 00:33:43.250
area.
 

00:33:43.250 --> 00:33:48.061
In other words,
dA and E are both

00:33:48.061 --> 00:33:52.769
parallel if the surface is a
sphere, right?

00:33:52.769 --> 00:33:55.740
So when you take the dot
product this will just become

00:33:55.740 --> 00:33:58.601
E(r) times
dA times cosine of 0

00:33:58.601 --> 00:34:00.339
which you don't care about.
 

00:34:00.339 --> 00:34:01.880
That's the first thing.
 

00:34:01.880 --> 00:34:04.328
You still have to integrate
over this sphere,

00:34:04.328 --> 00:34:07.667
but E of r is a
constant on this sphere because

00:34:07.667 --> 00:34:09.449
it depends only on r.
 

00:34:09.449 --> 00:34:12.018
So throughout the whole sphere
if it's a constant,

00:34:12.018 --> 00:34:16.440
it's like the number 19,
you just pull it and then you

00:34:16.440 --> 00:34:21.443
get E of r times
integral dA and that is

00:34:21.443 --> 00:34:23.530
my 4Πr^(2).
 

00:34:23.530 --> 00:34:26.865
So in general you have to do an
integral, but if you're lucky

00:34:26.865 --> 00:34:30.369
and the integrand is a constant
then the integral is trivial.

00:34:30.369 --> 00:34:34.244
So for a charge at the center
of the spherical ball,

00:34:34.244 --> 00:34:38.041
and if you went to a sphere
then the integrant is a

00:34:38.041 --> 00:34:39.030
constant.
 

00:34:39.030 --> 00:34:40.010
Okay, so this is what you get.
 

00:34:40.010 --> 00:34:43.000
If you draw a picture of this
it looks like this.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:49.467
Electric field as the function
of r it will grow with

00:34:49.467 --> 00:34:54.949
r then it will decline as
1/r^(2).

00:34:54.949 --> 00:34:59.030
And here is little r
equals big R.

00:34:59.030 --> 00:34:59.155
Yep?
 

00:34:59.155 --> 00:35:00.994
Student:  What if it
were hollow and all the charges

00:35:00.994 --> 00:35:02.010
were on the outside ________?
 

00:35:02.010 --> 00:35:04.230
Prof: We'll come to that.
 

00:35:04.230 --> 00:35:05.610
Yes?
 

00:35:05.610 --> 00:35:08.657
Student:  Why can we
ignore the charge that's outside

00:35:08.657 --> 00:35:09.639
the small sphere?
 

00:35:09.639 --> 00:35:11.099
Prof: Why don't we count
it?

00:35:11.099 --> 00:35:12.219
Student:  Uh-huh,
did you explain that already?

00:35:12.219 --> 00:35:14.105
Prof: Yeah,
well it's a very interesting

00:35:14.105 --> 00:35:14.719
point, right?
 

00:35:14.719 --> 00:35:17.735
Suppose you make a hole in the
earth, of if you go deep into

00:35:17.735 --> 00:35:18.349
the earth.
 

00:35:18.349 --> 00:35:21.777
We said if you're outside the
earth the entire ball is pulling

00:35:21.777 --> 00:35:23.710
you in,
but the claim I'm making is if

00:35:23.710 --> 00:35:25.726
you're inside the earth,
if you're here,

00:35:25.726 --> 00:35:28.590
only the ball underneath your
feet is pulling you,

00:35:28.590 --> 00:35:30.110
but not these guys, right?
 

00:35:30.110 --> 00:35:33.083
That's the question,
why don't they exert a force,

00:35:33.083 --> 00:35:33.570
right?
 

00:35:33.570 --> 00:35:40.902
Well, Gauss's Law says,
no, but we can try to verify

00:35:40.902 --> 00:35:43.489
that explicitly.
 

00:35:43.489 --> 00:35:46.545
So we are going to do the
hollow sphere,

00:35:46.545 --> 00:35:49.679
but you followed the solid
sphere now?

00:35:49.679 --> 00:35:52.349
So why is the field getting
stronger as you leave the

00:35:52.349 --> 00:35:55.378
center, why is it falling like
1/r^(2) once you leave

00:35:55.378 --> 00:35:56.150
the sphere?
 

00:35:56.150 --> 00:35:59.849
You've got to think about that.
 

00:35:59.849 --> 00:36:05.239
Why is it growing when you
leave the origin?

00:36:05.239 --> 00:36:06.369
Yep?
 

00:36:06.369 --> 00:36:08.550
Student:  Because there
is more charge _________.

00:36:08.550 --> 00:36:09.483
Prof: Right.
 

00:36:09.483 --> 00:36:11.793
The charge you are enclosing
grows like r cubed,

00:36:11.793 --> 00:36:14.300
and the distance from the
center of that charge is r

00:36:14.300 --> 00:36:16.070
squared which comes downstairs.
 

00:36:16.070 --> 00:36:19.239
So as you go further out inside
the ball you are gaining,

00:36:19.239 --> 00:36:22.061
but once you reach the surface
of the ball and you go further

00:36:22.061 --> 00:36:24.320
out you're getting more area for
Gauss's Law,

00:36:24.320 --> 00:36:27.610
but not more charge which is
stuck at capital Q.

00:36:27.610 --> 00:36:31.490
That's why once you leave the
sphere it starts declining,

00:36:31.490 --> 00:36:34.750
but if you're inside the sphere
it increases.

00:36:34.750 --> 00:36:36.510
This is also true for the
gravitational force.

00:36:36.510 --> 00:36:40.143
The gravitational force if you
go to the center of the earth

00:36:40.143 --> 00:36:43.594
and you move away by 1 inch
you'll be pulled back with an

00:36:43.594 --> 00:36:46.983
extremely weak force that's
proportional to the distance

00:36:46.983 --> 00:36:49.139
from the center of the earth.
 

00:36:49.139 --> 00:36:54.340
Okay, then we come to another
question which came up,

00:36:54.340 --> 00:36:58.139
which is let's take a hollow
sphere.

00:36:58.139 --> 00:37:10.989
I take a sphere and I scoop a
hole in it and I want the field

00:37:10.989 --> 00:37:12.489
here.
 

00:37:12.489 --> 00:37:16.436
Okay, so if you want the field
here you take a Gauss's Law for

00:37:16.436 --> 00:37:19.619
a circle like that,
or a sphere like that and

00:37:19.619 --> 00:37:23.561
you'll get E times
4Πr^(2) is equal to 1

00:37:23.561 --> 00:37:26.659
over ε_0 at
times what?

00:37:26.659 --> 00:37:28.130
Student:  Nothing.
 

00:37:28.130 --> 00:37:29.489
Prof: Nothing.
 

00:37:29.489 --> 00:37:34.239
So the electric field inside a
hollow sphere is 0.

00:37:34.239 --> 00:37:36.619
In other words,
if you took the earth and you

00:37:36.619 --> 00:37:39.269
scooped a big hole in the middle
you can float.

00:37:39.269 --> 00:37:42.789
It won't pull you at all.
 

00:37:42.789 --> 00:37:45.349
So inside a hollow sphere there
is no electric field.

00:37:45.349 --> 00:37:47.940
Even though there's charge
everywhere there's no electric

00:37:47.940 --> 00:37:48.309
field.
 

00:37:48.309 --> 00:37:51.764
We can understand that in some
cases, and other cases require a

00:37:51.764 --> 00:37:52.989
little more thought.
 

00:37:52.989 --> 00:37:57.166
Let me first show you that for
a very, very thin shell why that

00:37:57.166 --> 00:37:57.840
happens.
 

00:37:57.840 --> 00:38:00.387
Once it's true for a very,
very thin shell and it doesn't

00:38:00.387 --> 00:38:03.072
do anything you can put one
shell inside another and make it

00:38:03.072 --> 00:38:05.849
as thick as you like because 0
is going to be the contribution

00:38:05.849 --> 00:38:06.760
from each guy.
 

00:38:06.760 --> 00:38:08.889
So let me take a very thin
shell.

00:38:08.889 --> 00:38:11.539
Here's a very thin shell.
 

00:38:11.539 --> 00:38:14.030
So remember, this is not a ball.
 

00:38:14.030 --> 00:38:18.230
This is a shell whose thickness
is the thickness of the chalk

00:38:18.230 --> 00:38:18.719
here.
 

00:38:18.719 --> 00:38:22.311
I think you will agree that at
the center of this sphere the

00:38:22.311 --> 00:38:23.530
force has to be 0.
 

00:38:23.530 --> 00:38:25.949
You agree with that?
 

00:38:25.949 --> 00:38:27.760
Because which way should it go?
 

00:38:27.760 --> 00:38:29.974
For every guy pushing,
say from here in that

00:38:29.974 --> 00:38:32.858
direction, there's another one
from there pushing in this

00:38:32.858 --> 00:38:33.579
direction.
 

00:38:33.579 --> 00:38:35.750
They all cancel.
 

00:38:35.750 --> 00:38:38.099
It's very clear that at the
center you don't feel a force.

00:38:38.099 --> 00:38:43.873
But what is truly amazing is
that even when you're off center

00:38:43.873 --> 00:38:46.280
you don't feel a force.
 

00:38:46.280 --> 00:38:50.253
So I'm going to give you the
argument for that one,

00:38:50.253 --> 00:38:54.704
argument for that namely I'm
once again going to pair off

00:38:54.704 --> 00:38:56.929
canceling charges,
okay?

00:38:56.929 --> 00:39:00.480
I'm going to cancel one thing
against another thing.

00:39:00.480 --> 00:39:04.061
When you were at the center you
canceled a little charge here

00:39:04.061 --> 00:39:06.150
with a little charge here,
right?

00:39:06.150 --> 00:39:08.579
When you are here here's what
you do.

00:39:08.579 --> 00:39:16.469
Take a cone like that.
 

00:39:16.469 --> 00:39:17.518
It is not two lengths.
 

00:39:17.518 --> 00:39:20.923
It is a three dimensional cone,
but I'm able to show you only a

00:39:20.923 --> 00:39:23.449
slice right down the middle,
you understand?

00:39:23.449 --> 00:39:26.389
This is really a cone that'll
cut the sphere there;

00:39:26.389 --> 00:39:28.889
it'll cut the sphere there.
 

00:39:28.889 --> 00:39:30.900
Take all these guys.
 

00:39:30.900 --> 00:39:33.364
They have a certain charge,
which is some charge density

00:39:33.364 --> 00:39:37.507
which is uniform,
times the area of this thing

00:39:37.507 --> 00:39:44.469
divided by the square of the
distance r_1.

00:39:44.469 --> 00:39:47.733
Here, these charges here will
push you to the right with a

00:39:47.733 --> 00:39:49.909
force which is the area of
density,

00:39:49.909 --> 00:39:54.635
the charge density per unit
area times the area of the

00:39:54.635 --> 00:39:59.719
smaller circle divided by
r_2 squared.

00:39:59.719 --> 00:40:15.018
But now I claim that I can
equate these two.

00:40:15.018 --> 00:40:19.018
I can equate these two if this
area of vector and this area of

00:40:19.018 --> 00:40:22.822
vector were radiating outwards,
and this is actually a true

00:40:22.822 --> 00:40:23.739
statement.
 

00:40:23.739 --> 00:40:25.518
This area is proportional to
r_1 squared.

00:40:25.518 --> 00:40:32.764
This area is proportional to
r_1 squared,

00:40:32.764 --> 00:40:36.449
therefore they will cancel.
 

00:40:36.449 --> 00:40:38.449
But this is a very subtle
argument.

00:40:38.449 --> 00:40:41.170
Sometimes even textbooks get it
wrong.

00:40:41.170 --> 00:40:46.409
And generally if you take two
cones like this you can see that

00:40:46.409 --> 00:40:51.650
the area vector points that way,
but the electric field vector

00:40:51.650 --> 00:40:53.369
points this way.
 

00:40:53.369 --> 00:40:54.440
They are not the same.
 

00:40:54.440 --> 00:40:56.742
The area vector,
area on the sphere,

00:40:56.742 --> 00:40:59.769
right, will point in one
direction, but the

00:40:59.769 --> 00:41:02.349
r vector is different.
 

00:41:02.349 --> 00:41:06.789
So you have to take the cosine
θ on both sides,

00:41:06.789 --> 00:41:10.083
but it turns out cosine
θ is also the same

00:41:10.083 --> 00:41:13.744
because if you took a line and
you cut it this way that angle

00:41:13.744 --> 00:41:15.329
will equal that angle.
 

00:41:15.329 --> 00:41:18.476
So that's a subtly we don't
need, but that's how you really

00:41:18.476 --> 00:41:19.780
prove for every shell.
 

00:41:19.780 --> 00:41:20.909
There's a cancellation.
 

00:41:20.909 --> 00:41:23.190
If you know what a solid angle
is it's very easy to say.

00:41:23.190 --> 00:41:26.050
This is called,
with the cosine thetas in it,

00:41:26.050 --> 00:41:29.510
it's called a solid angle
enclosed by this point,

00:41:29.510 --> 00:41:32.476
and the two things have the
same solid angle and they

00:41:32.476 --> 00:41:32.989
cancel.
 

