I draw a line,
a plane of charges here and

00:55:44.030 --> 00:55:46.230
here, and you can see they will
cancel.

00:55:46.230 --> 00:55:49.690
But even this oddball object,
I claim,

00:55:49.690 --> 00:55:52.059
will eventually acquire some
density of charges,

00:55:52.059 --> 00:55:55.987
they're not uniform or
anything, in some complicated

00:55:55.987 --> 00:56:00.070
fashion until the field inside
the solid becomes 0.

00:56:00.070 --> 00:56:05.407
So these particles will always
figure out a way to make the

00:56:05.407 --> 00:56:09.639
field 0 inside,
because it's the definition.

00:56:09.639 --> 00:56:12.489
If it's not 0 they've got more
work to do,

00:56:12.489 --> 00:56:15.503
and the charges have to
separate even more until there

00:56:15.503 --> 00:56:19.030
is no hunger for the separation
because they managed to produce

00:56:19.030 --> 00:56:20.679
a field inside that is 0.
 

00:56:20.679 --> 00:56:23.579
Then nobody else will join this
flow and it'll stop.

00:56:23.579 --> 00:56:26.947
So that's a very short period,
10 to the minus something,

00:56:26.947 --> 00:56:30.556
when charges rearrange when you
put a conductor in the field,

00:56:30.556 --> 00:56:32.239
then quickly it'll stop.
 

00:56:32.239 --> 00:56:35.130
If you put an alternating field
going back and forth then,

00:56:35.130 --> 00:56:37.530
of course, it depends on how
rapidly it's oscillating,

00:56:37.530 --> 00:56:39.880
and charges may not be able to
keep up with that.

00:56:39.880 --> 00:56:42.650
That's called a plasma
frequency, and beyond that a

00:56:42.650 --> 00:56:45.920
field would start penetrating
because charges cannot keep in

00:56:45.920 --> 00:56:46.420
step.
 

00:56:46.420 --> 00:56:48.268
But a DC field,
where you've got all the time

00:56:48.268 --> 00:56:50.706
in the world to settle down,
they will very quickly come to

00:56:50.706 --> 00:56:51.590
this arrangement.
 

00:56:51.590 --> 00:56:53.309
They will stop.
 

00:56:53.309 --> 00:56:59.389
So remember field in a
conductor is 0 by definition.

00:56:59.389 --> 00:57:14.369
Okay, now the next thing I will
show you is that charge inside a

00:57:14.369 --> 00:57:19.840
conductor equal to 0.
 

00:57:19.840 --> 00:57:22.268
By that I mean the following.
 

00:57:22.268 --> 00:57:28.474
If you took a conductor and you
threw some charge on it where

00:57:28.474 --> 00:57:29.820
will it go?
 

00:57:29.820 --> 00:57:31.340
Okay, here's a chunk of copper.
 

00:57:31.340 --> 00:57:33.780
Throw 10 million electrons.
 

00:57:33.780 --> 00:57:35.820
Well, the 10 million electrons
don't like each other.

00:57:35.820 --> 00:57:37.960
They will try to run away from
each other.

00:57:37.960 --> 00:57:41.954
In the end they will all sit
somewhere here,

00:57:41.954 --> 00:57:47.344
but they will sit in such a way
that the field inside is 0,

00:57:47.344 --> 00:57:51.619
because you cannot have an
electric field.

00:57:51.619 --> 00:57:54.333
If the electric field is 0
everywhere then the charge is

00:57:54.333 --> 00:57:56.327
also 0 everywhere,
because you can take any

00:57:56.327 --> 00:57:58.242
surface, any volume you like
with the integral of

00:57:58.242 --> 00:58:02.159
E⋅dA,
you're going to get 0.

00:58:02.159 --> 00:58:04.909
If you can get
E⋅dA is 0 for

00:58:04.909 --> 00:58:08.195
every possible surface then the
charge enclosed by every

00:58:08.195 --> 00:58:11.449
possible surface is 0,
therefore there is no charge in

00:58:11.449 --> 00:58:11.820
sight.
 

00:58:11.820 --> 00:58:13.329
So where does the charge go?
 

00:58:13.329 --> 00:58:15.900
It goes to the boundary of the
metal.

00:58:15.900 --> 00:58:19.849
Once they're at the boundary of
the metal the metal starts

00:58:19.849 --> 00:58:23.728
calling you back because there
is something called a work

00:58:23.728 --> 00:58:24.630
function.
 

00:58:24.630 --> 00:58:27.289
It's like all the electrons in
a swimming pool.

00:58:27.289 --> 00:58:29.155
If they don't like each other
they can go to the edge of the

00:58:29.155 --> 00:58:30.512
pool,
but to leave the pool they've

00:58:30.512 --> 00:58:32.110
got to climb up over the
vertical walls,

00:58:32.110 --> 00:58:34.619
and they cannot scale the walls.
 

00:58:34.619 --> 00:58:36.340
If you rip them hard enough
they will.

00:58:36.340 --> 00:58:39.273
If you put enough charges,
charges will start flying from

00:58:39.273 --> 00:58:43.018
here and maybe land there;
that we call lightening.

00:58:43.018 --> 00:58:47.351
For that they'll have to break
the air and produce a conducting

00:58:47.351 --> 00:58:51.612
path, but if you don't put such
strong fields the charges will

00:58:51.612 --> 00:58:53.429
remain on the surface.
 

00:58:53.429 --> 00:58:57.487
Now, it turns out we can
actually relate the electric

00:58:57.487 --> 00:59:02.092
field at the surface to the
charge density of the surface by

00:59:02.092 --> 00:59:03.809
a following trick.
 

00:59:03.809 --> 00:59:05.686
Let's go to the surface here
and ask, "What's the

00:59:05.686 --> 00:59:06.289
electric field?
 

00:59:06.289 --> 00:59:07.909
Which way can it point?"
 

00:59:07.909 --> 00:59:14.085
I claim the electric field can
only point perpendicular to the

00:59:14.085 --> 00:59:16.494
surface,
because if you had parallel

00:59:16.494 --> 00:59:19.179
components then the charges can
move along the surface.

00:59:19.179 --> 00:59:21.746
No one says you cannot run it
on the edge of the swimming

00:59:21.746 --> 00:59:23.260
pool, you just cannot leave it.
 

00:59:23.260 --> 00:59:26.771
So the electric field lines
must point radial,

00:59:26.771 --> 00:59:29.268
I mean, normal to the surface.
 

00:59:29.268 --> 00:59:32.739
And I claim that we can
actually calculate the electric

00:59:32.739 --> 00:59:35.889
field here if you knew the
charge density here.

00:59:35.889 --> 00:59:37.570
So let's do that.
 

00:59:37.570 --> 00:59:43.851
So here's some surface,
and I have--take a tiny region

00:59:43.851 --> 00:59:50.963
here and I'm going to take a
Gaussian surface that looks like

00:59:50.963 --> 00:59:52.030
this.
 

00:59:52.030 --> 00:59:54.983
It's a cylinder,
very tiny cylinder,

00:59:54.983 --> 00:59:58.530
and the field lines are like
that there.

00:59:58.530 --> 01:00:02.050
There is no field lines here
because there's no field inside.

01:00:02.050 --> 01:00:05.501
And the field here all of these
things are 0,

01:00:05.501 --> 01:00:10.132
and the field here is parallel
to the cylinder so it doesn't

01:00:10.132 --> 01:00:11.309
contribute.
 

01:00:11.309 --> 01:00:11.880
You see that?
 

01:00:11.880 --> 01:00:12.699
I got a cylinder.
 

01:00:12.699 --> 01:00:14.150
I rammed it into this solid.
 

01:00:14.150 --> 01:00:17.110
It's a mathematical Gaussian
surface.

01:00:17.110 --> 01:00:19.820
It's got following faces,
flat face,

01:00:19.820 --> 01:00:22.409
no E because there's
nothing inside the metal,

01:00:22.409 --> 01:00:24.400
this part of the curvy-face,
no E,

01:00:24.400 --> 01:00:25.949
nothing inside the metal.
 

01:00:25.949 --> 01:00:28.447
Here E is parallel to
the sides of the cylinder,

01:00:28.447 --> 01:00:29.420
so there's no flux.
 

01:00:29.420 --> 01:00:32.512
The top end,
if the area's A or

01:00:32.512 --> 01:00:35.534
dA,
the top end will have a flux

01:00:35.534 --> 01:00:39.681
which will be the E that
I'm trying to calculate times

01:00:39.681 --> 01:00:40.579
dA.
 

01:00:40.579 --> 01:00:44.271
That's going to be equal to the
charge enclosed is

01:00:44.271 --> 01:00:48.039
σdA/
ε_0,

01:00:48.039 --> 01:00:52.474
because σ
is the charge density which I

01:00:52.474 --> 01:00:54.389
assume I'm given.
 

01:00:54.389 --> 01:00:57.239
Then you can see the dA
cancels.

01:00:57.239 --> 01:01:11.018
The electric field is
σ/ε_0.

01:01:11.018 --> 01:01:15.932
Do you remember ever seeing a
formula like this sigma or

01:01:15.932 --> 01:01:17.809
anything like this?
 

01:01:17.809 --> 01:01:24.860
Yes?
 

01:01:24.860 --> 01:01:25.480
Okay.
 

01:01:25.480 --> 01:01:33.679
Let me remind you where you saw
it.

01:01:33.679 --> 01:01:38.867
I showed you that if you took
an infinite plane of charge

01:01:38.867 --> 01:01:42.295
density σ
the electric field was

01:01:42.295 --> 01:01:47.215
σ/2ε_0,
and I did that with a long

01:01:47.215 --> 01:01:48.010
calculation.
 

01:01:48.010 --> 01:01:48.920
I took a point there.
 

01:01:48.920 --> 01:01:51.050
I took rings and so on.
 

01:01:51.050 --> 01:01:53.268
Now, you don't have to do that.
 

01:01:53.268 --> 01:01:56.570
Let's use Gauss's Law again to
calculate it.

01:01:56.570 --> 01:01:59.902
Once again, you argue that if
you're in front of an infinite

01:01:59.902 --> 01:02:03.349
plane the only distribution of
field lines that makes sense is

01:02:03.349 --> 01:02:06.739
if the field line's always
perpendicular to the surface.

01:02:06.739 --> 01:02:08.929
They can get weaker as you go
away,

01:02:08.929 --> 01:02:11.240
but at a given distance from
the plane they should have the

01:02:11.240 --> 01:02:13.684
same value,
because if you slide the plane

01:02:13.684 --> 01:02:15.760
up and down it shouldn't matter.
 

01:02:15.760 --> 01:02:17.809
So let's take the side view of
the plane.

01:02:17.809 --> 01:02:19.869
There are your charges.
 

01:02:19.869 --> 01:02:23.090
And I'm going to take a
Gaussian cylinder that looks

01:02:23.090 --> 01:02:23.849
like this.
 

01:02:23.849 --> 01:02:26.409
The field lines are going like
that.

01:02:26.409 --> 01:02:27.518
They're going like that.
 

01:02:27.518 --> 01:02:30.409
There is some charge trapped
here.

01:02:30.409 --> 01:02:37.670
And the area of that guy is
some dA.

01:02:37.670 --> 01:02:40.268
So again, I apply Gauss's Law
here.

01:02:40.268 --> 01:02:43.610
Of the cylinder I got the curvy
sides with no contribution,

01:02:43.610 --> 01:02:46.489
because the field is parallel
to the curvy side.

01:02:46.489 --> 01:02:48.429
I got the flat faces.
 

01:02:48.429 --> 01:02:50.961
So I get E times
dA for one of them,

01:02:50.961 --> 01:02:53.338
and E times dA
for the other one,

01:02:53.338 --> 01:02:54.889
because both are outgoing.
 

01:02:54.889 --> 01:02:57.579
That is equal to charge
enclosed with the σ

01:02:57.579 --> 01:03:00.440
times dA divided by
ε_0.

01:03:00.440 --> 01:03:05.039
If you cancel the dA you
find E is

01:03:05.039 --> 01:03:08.268
σ/2ε_0.
 

01:03:08.268 --> 01:03:10.856
So the electric field on either
side of the plane is

01:03:10.856 --> 01:03:12.530
σ/2ε_0.
 

01:03:12.530 --> 01:03:14.369
You just get it from Gauss's
Law.

01:03:14.369 --> 01:03:18.380
Again, there's no reason to do
the complicated integral.

01:03:18.380 --> 01:03:20.900
That's because we've reduced
everything to one unknown,

01:03:20.900 --> 01:03:23.469
namely what was the magnitude
of the electric field at a

01:03:23.469 --> 01:03:25.150
certain distance from the plane?
 

01:03:25.150 --> 01:03:28.485
Direction is known to be
perpendicular and to be constant

01:03:28.485 --> 01:03:29.380
on this line.
 

01:03:29.380 --> 01:03:33.369
Then the one number came out to
be, in fact, independent of how

01:03:33.369 --> 01:03:34.268
far you are.
 

01:03:34.268 --> 01:03:36.929
But now go back to the
conductor.

01:03:36.929 --> 01:03:41.541
If you go back to the conductor
you find the field at the

01:03:41.541 --> 01:03:45.989
surface of a conductor is
σ/ε_0

01:03:45.989 --> 01:03:49.860
where σ
is the charge density there,

01:03:49.860 --> 01:03:51.534
whereas for an infinite plane
it's

01:03:51.534 --> 01:03:53.969
σ/2ε_0
on either side.

01:03:53.969 --> 01:03:56.018
And you can ask,
what's going on?

01:03:56.018 --> 01:04:00.050
Why is it
σ/ε_0?

01:04:00.050 --> 01:04:04.980
Can anybody guess what may be
happening?

01:04:04.980 --> 01:04:07.135
In other words,
if you take a tiny area on a

01:04:07.135 --> 01:04:10.523
conductor and you go very,
very, very close it should be

01:04:10.523 --> 01:04:13.260
as if you're next to an infinite
plane,

01:04:13.260 --> 01:04:15.594
because if you're very,
very close to the surface you

01:04:15.594 --> 01:04:17.389
don't know if it's finite or
infinite.

01:04:17.389 --> 01:04:19.989
So you should get the same
answer as for the infinite

01:04:19.989 --> 01:04:20.389
plane.
 

01:04:20.389 --> 01:04:24.815
Therefore, if you took only the
charge sitting there it should

01:04:24.815 --> 01:04:27.572
give you
σ/2ε_0

01:04:27.572 --> 01:04:30.690
going out and
σ/2ε_0

01:04:30.690 --> 01:04:31.780
going in.
 

01:04:31.780 --> 01:04:33.010
In other words,
let me draw a picture here.

01:04:33.010 --> 01:04:34.380
That's my tiny area.
 

01:04:34.380 --> 01:04:38.887
I expect the field due to just
the charge there to be like

01:04:38.887 --> 01:04:41.940
this,
σ/2ε_0,

01:04:41.940 --> 01:04:46.710
and
σ/2ε_0.

01:04:46.710 --> 01:04:51.157
But that is not the whole story
because I've got the rest of the

01:04:51.157 --> 01:04:53.840
conductor that's got its own
charge.

01:04:53.840 --> 01:04:56.789
It is going to produce a field.
 

01:04:56.789 --> 01:05:00.831
That field will have some
value, and I claim I know the

01:05:00.831 --> 01:05:02.480
value of that field.
 

01:05:02.480 --> 01:05:07.219
It'll be precisely enough to
cancel it on the inside,

01:05:07.219 --> 01:05:10.818
but if you cancel it on the
inside you'll double it on the

01:05:10.818 --> 01:05:14.228
outside because it's got
σ/2ε_0

01:05:14.228 --> 01:05:16.880
pointing outwards to cancel this
guy,

01:05:16.880 --> 01:05:20.849
but then it'll aid the one due
to the little area by doubling

01:05:20.849 --> 01:05:21.179
it.
 

01:05:21.179 --> 01:05:23.471
That's why it's
σ/ε_0

01:05:23.471 --> 01:05:24.670
outside and 0 inside.
 

01:05:24.670 --> 01:05:26.539
In other words,
here is the full story.

01:05:26.539 --> 01:05:29.981
If you go to a conductor,
if you pick a region here,

01:05:29.981 --> 01:05:33.760
the field at this point is due
to what's here and what is

01:05:33.760 --> 01:05:35.110
everywhere else.
 

01:05:35.110 --> 01:05:39.030
What is here does that as if it
was an infinite plane.

01:05:39.030 --> 01:05:45.849
The rest of the guys do that
and that cancels this here,

01:05:45.849 --> 01:05:50.063
but adds there,
so you can see more

01:05:50.063 --> 01:05:54.280
ε_0 outside.
 

01:05:54.280 --> 01:05:57.050
Okay, then there are other
variations to this theme.

01:05:57.050 --> 01:06:01.045
So here's a conductor,
and I make a hole in it,

01:06:01.045 --> 01:06:03.130
and I put some charge.
 

01:06:03.130 --> 01:06:07.940
You can ask if I throw some
charge on it where will it sit.

01:06:07.940 --> 01:06:12.971
Well, some charges will sit
here if you put some coulombs,

01:06:12.971 --> 01:06:16.590
but what will happen on the
inner wall?

01:06:16.590 --> 01:06:21.190
This is a hole.
 

01:06:21.190 --> 01:06:23.929
The claim is that there'll be
no charges here.

01:06:23.929 --> 01:06:26.889
They'll all be outside even
though you've got a hole in the

01:06:26.889 --> 01:06:27.349
middle.
 

01:06:27.349 --> 01:06:29.719
Again, Gauss's Law tells you
why.

01:06:29.719 --> 01:06:33.175
If I take a surface like this
and do Gauss's Law,

01:06:33.175 --> 01:06:36.485
since the electric field is 0
inside the metal,

01:06:36.485 --> 01:06:38.429
Q enclosed is 0.
 

01:06:38.429 --> 01:06:40.960
So the Q that's
enclosed, which is 0,

01:06:40.960 --> 01:06:45.119
means that maybe some positive
guys and some negative guys,

01:06:45.119 --> 01:06:48.619
but there's nothing from
stopping the positive guys from

01:06:48.619 --> 01:06:51.800
rushing to meet the negative
guys and canceling.

01:06:51.800 --> 01:06:53.670
They will, for there is no
reason they just stay on

01:06:53.670 --> 01:06:54.829
opposite sides of the island.
 

01:06:54.829 --> 01:06:58.280
They'll just come together.
 

01:06:58.280 --> 01:07:01.657
Therefore, there is no stable
equilibrium in which the charges

01:07:01.657 --> 01:07:03.539
will be ever inside a conductor.
 

01:07:03.539 --> 01:07:07.510
So if you have a conductor and
you put charge on it,

01:07:07.510 --> 01:07:11.869
it goes to the surface even if
there are holes inside the

01:07:11.869 --> 01:07:12.960
conductor.
 

01:07:12.960 --> 01:07:15.539
Now, that's a very interesting
paradox.

01:07:15.539 --> 01:07:19.023
I showed you that the field
inside a conductor even if

01:07:19.023 --> 01:07:22.114
there's a hole is 0,
but let's ask the following

01:07:22.114 --> 01:07:22.969
question.
 

01:07:22.969 --> 01:07:26.672
I take a conductor with the
hole in it and I put a charge

01:07:26.672 --> 01:07:27.730
q here.
 

01:07:27.730 --> 01:07:32.239
Will you know about it from the
outside?

01:07:32.239 --> 01:07:33.510
You're not allowed to enter it.
 

01:07:33.510 --> 01:07:38.969
Will you know from the outside
there's a charge inside or will

01:07:38.969 --> 01:07:41.030
it get also shielded?
 

01:07:41.030 --> 01:07:47.460
Will there be any flux lines
coming out here?

01:07:47.460 --> 01:07:47.780
Yep?
 

01:07:47.780 --> 01:07:48.949
Student:  Yes.
 

01:07:48.949 --> 01:07:49.880
Prof: Because?
 

01:07:49.880 --> 01:07:52.230
Student:  Because
there's a charge.

01:07:52.230 --> 01:07:52.730
Prof: Right.
 

01:07:52.730 --> 01:07:57.255
If there are no field lines
here, and I do Gauss's Law on

01:07:57.255 --> 01:07:59.769
this surface,
if the surface integral of

01:07:59.769 --> 01:08:01.788
E is 0
q_enclosed is

01:08:01.788 --> 01:08:05.112
0,
but I know there is some

01:08:05.112 --> 01:08:07.269
q inside.
 

01:08:07.269 --> 01:08:09.210
So what's going to happen?
 

01:08:09.210 --> 01:08:13.820
I want the field lines to be
present here and absent here.

01:08:13.820 --> 01:08:17.993
So what'll happen is if you put
a q here the material

01:08:17.993 --> 01:08:22.024
conductor will separate into
-q's where these lines

01:08:22.024 --> 01:08:27.305
can terminate,
and then out here will be some

01:08:27.305 --> 01:08:33.863
compensating plus charges
that'll produce the field

01:08:33.863 --> 01:08:38.979
that'll produce the lines going
out.

01:08:38.979 --> 01:08:43.123
In other words,
this is really like a chunk of

01:08:43.123 --> 01:08:48.557
copper I showed you where it
screens the field by polarizing

01:08:48.557 --> 01:08:53.899
into a negative part in this
wall and positive contribution

01:08:53.899 --> 01:08:59.149
in the outer wall so that inside
there is no field.

01:08:59.149 --> 01:09:03.680
Okay, so these are different
variations of this theme and you

01:09:03.680 --> 01:09:08.210
should be able to do a whole
bunch of problems connected with

01:09:08.210 --> 01:09:08.890
that.
 

01:09:08.890 --> 01:09:13.850
Okay, I've used up my board,
so I think I'll give you guys a

01:09:13.850 --> 01:09:18.895
five minute tour on how to do
these integrals in case it ever

01:09:18.895 --> 01:09:19.988
comes up.
 

01:09:19.988 --> 01:09:22.659
I'm just going to do two very
trivial integrals and stop,

01:09:22.659 --> 01:09:25.474
and I'm going to do them in two
dimensions and you can worry

01:09:25.474 --> 01:09:26.810
about higher dimensions.
 

01:09:26.810 --> 01:09:28.640
It's just generalization.
 

01:09:28.640 --> 01:09:34.778
Suppose you're in the xy
plane and there's a function in

01:09:34.778 --> 01:09:39.827
the xy plane,
f (x, y), and someone says find

01:09:39.827 --> 01:09:41.609
f (x,y) dx dy.
 

01:09:41.609 --> 01:09:45.283
What's the procedure and what
are you supposed to do is the

01:09:45.283 --> 01:09:45.979
question.
 

01:09:45.979 --> 01:09:49.225
What you do in Cartesian
coordinates is you take a line

01:09:49.225 --> 01:09:52.481
y equal to something,
y equal to something

01:09:52.481 --> 01:09:54.621
delta y,
x equal to something,

01:09:54.621 --> 01:09:56.649
x equal to something
delta x,

01:09:56.649 --> 01:09:59.063
and that region (bounded) by
these contours of constant

01:09:59.063 --> 01:10:01.832
x at different values and
constant y at different

01:10:01.832 --> 01:10:05.380
values,
has an area dxdy.

01:10:05.380 --> 01:10:08.390
You multiply that area by this
function.

01:10:08.390 --> 01:10:10.655
This could be the number of
people living per square mile

01:10:10.655 --> 01:10:12.600
and this could be the number of
square miles,

01:10:12.600 --> 01:10:16.649
and you add up all the little
squares over the area that was

01:10:16.649 --> 01:10:17.680
given to you.
 

01:10:17.680 --> 01:10:21.567
So whoever tells you to do
integrals better tell you over

01:10:21.567 --> 01:10:24.760
what range you're going to do
that integral.

01:10:24.760 --> 01:10:26.600
Okay?
 

01:10:26.600 --> 01:10:33.979
So let's find out the area for
triangle by this process.

01:10:33.979 --> 01:10:35.788
Here's a triangle.
 

01:10:35.788 --> 01:10:40.289
Let's say there's one here and
one here, 0,1;

01:10:40.289 --> 01:10:41.279
