01:12:50.359 --> 01:12:55.373
But the final thing I'm going
to do is to do the same integral

01:12:55.373 --> 01:12:59.319
in polar coordinates,
area of a triangle in polar

01:12:59.319 --> 01:13:01.948
coordinates looks like this.
 

01:13:01.948 --> 01:13:04.670
In polar coordinates,
as you know,

01:13:04.670 --> 01:13:08.738
you draw circles of r
and r dr,

01:13:08.738 --> 01:13:12.920
and lines at θ and
θ dθ,

01:13:12.920 --> 01:13:17.307
and this shaded region here has
got one side equal to

01:13:17.307 --> 01:13:22.118
rdθ and the other
side equal to dr.

01:13:22.118 --> 01:13:26.787
So area integral will look like
rdrdθ times some

01:13:26.787 --> 01:13:31.065
function of r and
θ over the allowed

01:13:31.065 --> 01:13:35.177
region,
but I want to do now a triangle

01:13:35.177 --> 01:13:37.640
of height 1 and base 1.
 

01:13:37.640 --> 01:13:39.729
Here's what I do.
 

01:13:39.729 --> 01:13:43.091
I'm going to pick theta first
and hold it fixed,

01:13:43.091 --> 01:13:45.739
and theta will go from 0 to
Π/4.

01:13:45.739 --> 01:13:46.819
Can you see that?
 

01:13:46.819 --> 01:13:48.970
This is supposed to be a square.
 

01:13:48.970 --> 01:13:52.282
Theta goes from 0 to
Π/4,

01:13:52.282 --> 01:13:54.619
and I have rdr.
 

01:13:54.619 --> 01:13:58.689
What is the range of r?
 

01:13:58.689 --> 01:14:00.500
How far is this thing?
 

01:14:00.500 --> 01:14:03.935
You can see that if this angle
is theta then

01:14:03.935 --> 01:14:07.931
rcosθ is 1,
and for r is

01:14:07.931 --> 01:14:09.850
1/cosθ.
 

01:14:09.850 --> 01:14:14.640
So r dr is really
d of r squared.

01:14:14.640 --> 01:14:21.226
d of r squared is
equal to d of

01:14:21.226 --> 01:14:25.489
1/cos^(2)θ,
right?

01:14:25.489 --> 01:14:26.439
I mean, let me do it this way.
 

01:14:26.439 --> 01:14:34.742
d of r squared is
r^(2)/2 from 1/cosθ

01:14:34.742 --> 01:14:36.288
to 0.
 

01:14:36.288 --> 01:14:43.890
So that gives me 1/2 integral
dθ 0 to Π/4 of

01:14:43.890 --> 01:14:47.238
1/cos^(2)θ.
 

01:14:47.238 --> 01:14:50.229
Well, you may not know this,
but sec^(2)θ is

01:14:50.229 --> 01:14:52.260
the derivative of
tanθ.

01:14:52.260 --> 01:14:56.661
So derivative of integral of
tanθ will turn out

01:14:56.661 --> 01:15:00.764
to be simply tanθ
calculated between Π/4

01:15:00.764 --> 01:15:01.510
and 0.
 

01:15:01.510 --> 01:15:04.939
That'll be just 1.
 

01:15:04.939 --> 01:15:08.000
So you're not supposed to
follow at lightening speed this

01:15:08.000 --> 01:15:08.930
integral, okay?
 

01:15:08.930 --> 01:15:11.740
